1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,460
 [MUSIC PLAYING]

2
00:00:09,460 --> 00:00:10,580
 Hello.

3
00:00:10,580 --> 00:00:12,460
 I have a confession to make.

4
00:00:12,460 --> 00:00:13,980
 Perhaps you've taken a class from me

5
00:00:13,980 --> 00:00:20,420
 where I misled you on what's going on in Python.

6
00:00:20,420 --> 00:00:23,220
 First, we've got to take a look into the past.

7
00:00:23,220 --> 00:00:27,460
 The following two slides are from chapter two of my Python

8
00:00:27,460 --> 00:00:30,400
 for everybody textbook and course that's

9
00:00:30,400 --> 00:00:32,460
 available all over the place.

10
00:00:32,460 --> 00:00:36,060
 It's introduced more people to programming in the millions

11
00:00:36,060 --> 00:00:38,500
 than any other course in the world.

12
00:00:38,500 --> 00:00:40,460
 These slides are misleading.

13
00:00:40,460 --> 00:00:44,140
 And at worst, they are 100% wrong.

14
00:00:44,140 --> 00:00:47,580
 Let's take a look at the slides and see why.

15
00:00:47,580 --> 00:00:48,980
 Here's a slide.

16
00:00:48,980 --> 00:00:51,340
 It's like the fifth slide of that class.

17
00:00:51,340 --> 00:00:53,340
 A variable is a named place in memory

18
00:00:53,340 --> 00:00:55,580
 where a programmer can store data and then later

19
00:00:55,580 --> 00:00:57,980
 retrieve it using the name of the variable.

20
00:00:57,980 --> 00:01:00,140
 Programmers get to choose the names of the variables.

21
00:01:00,140 --> 00:01:01,820
 They're like labels in memory location.

22
00:01:01,820 --> 00:01:04,180
 And you can change the contents of a variable

23
00:01:04,180 --> 00:01:05,500
 in a later statement.

24
00:01:05,500 --> 00:01:08,580
 So x equals 12 takes a little drawer, labels it x,

25
00:01:08,580 --> 00:01:10,140
 puts a 12 in there.

26
00:01:10,140 --> 00:01:14,980
 y equals 14 puts a 14 in a drawer and labels it y.

27
00:01:14,980 --> 00:01:18,820
 But then if you change it like x equals 100 later,

28
00:01:18,820 --> 00:01:24,700
 that replaces the value 12.2 with the value 100.

29
00:01:24,700 --> 00:01:26,660
 This is what's really happening.

30
00:01:26,660 --> 00:01:29,340
 A Python variable is a symbolic name

31
00:01:29,340 --> 00:01:34,140
 that is a pointer or reference to an object.

32
00:01:34,140 --> 00:01:36,020
 You can kind of see why I didn't explain this

33
00:01:36,020 --> 00:01:37,420
 in the very beginning.

34
00:01:37,420 --> 00:01:39,460
 We actually can use the ID function

35
00:01:39,460 --> 00:01:43,420
 to say, where is this variable pointing to?

36
00:01:43,420 --> 00:01:47,620
 Now, not all Pythons-- this is the CPython, the Python that

37
00:01:47,620 --> 00:01:50,500
 is written in C, the CPython.

38
00:01:50,500 --> 00:01:53,060
 We can ask it, where is it?

39
00:01:53,060 --> 00:01:55,460
 So if we say x equals 42 and then y equals x,

40
00:01:55,460 --> 00:01:58,460
 you'd think that'd be two locations in memory.

41
00:01:58,460 --> 00:01:59,740
 But it's not.

42
00:01:59,740 --> 00:02:02,620
 It's two pointers to one location in memory.

43
00:02:02,620 --> 00:02:04,420
 And we can figure this out by saying,

44
00:02:04,420 --> 00:02:07,540
 print id of x, which is like, hey, where

45
00:02:07,540 --> 00:02:09,180
 would we find x in memory?

46
00:02:09,180 --> 00:02:10,140
 And it's got a number.

47
00:02:10,140 --> 00:02:15,300
 And then we say, print id of y, and it's the same place.

48
00:02:15,300 --> 00:02:19,020
 So we only have 142.

49
00:02:19,020 --> 00:02:20,620
 We don't have two 42s.

50
00:02:20,620 --> 00:02:22,780
 But we have an x pointer and a y pointer

51
00:02:22,780 --> 00:02:23,700
 that points to it.

52
00:02:23,700 --> 00:02:29,500
 So for example, we can say, take the object 300.

53
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:31,180
 It's an integer.

54
00:02:31,180 --> 00:02:33,140
 We say x equals 300.

55
00:02:33,140 --> 00:02:36,020
 The 300 exists somewhere.

56
00:02:36,020 --> 00:02:39,060
 And x, when we say x equals 300, it

57
00:02:39,060 --> 00:02:41,820
 points at that object that exists somewhere.

58
00:02:41,820 --> 00:02:44,060
 And it has a location.

59
00:02:44,060 --> 00:02:47,260
 And then what happens, if we say x equals 2,000,

60
00:02:47,260 --> 00:02:51,340
 the 2,000 is a different object in a different location.

61
00:02:51,340 --> 00:02:54,420
 And x then points to the 2,000.

62
00:02:54,420 --> 00:02:57,880
 The old object, integer 300, may still be there.

63
00:02:57,880 --> 00:02:59,860
 But it's on what we'd call a free list.

64
00:02:59,860 --> 00:03:01,260
 Some might be on a free list.

65
00:03:01,260 --> 00:03:05,620
 But the idea is that you're changing the pointer x

66
00:03:05,620 --> 00:03:08,940
 to point to the integer 2,000, rather than changing

67
00:03:08,940 --> 00:03:12,260
 the contents of a drawer labeled x to be 2,000.

68
00:03:12,260 --> 00:03:13,940
 Again, if we say y equals x, you'll

69
00:03:13,940 --> 00:03:17,140
 see that y does not make a copy of 2,000.

70
00:03:17,140 --> 00:03:22,060
 It simply points to where the same 2,000 that x is pointing

71
00:03:22,060 --> 00:03:22,620
 to.

72
00:03:22,620 --> 00:03:27,380
 So y equals x says, take the address that x points to

73
00:03:27,380 --> 00:03:30,880
 and put that address in y.

74
00:03:30,880 --> 00:03:34,940
 Now, if we switch to more complex objects like a list,

75
00:03:34,940 --> 00:03:37,060
 it makes a little more sense.

76
00:03:37,060 --> 00:03:39,980
 x equals list says, let's make a list.

77
00:03:39,980 --> 00:03:42,200
 And we can say, print ID of x.

78
00:03:42,200 --> 00:03:44,860
 And that says, this is where it's at.

79
00:03:44,860 --> 00:03:47,140
 And we can append hello to it.

80
00:03:47,140 --> 00:03:50,820
 Now, the thing is, that didn't change where x was.

81
00:03:50,820 --> 00:03:53,220
 But it did change what was in x.

82
00:03:53,220 --> 00:03:55,900
 So x append hello adds hello to the end of my list.

83
00:03:55,900 --> 00:03:57,460
 And I can say, where's x?

84
00:03:57,460 --> 00:03:58,540
 Print ID of x.

85
00:03:58,540 --> 00:04:01,660
 And it's in the same location.

86
00:04:01,660 --> 00:04:03,780
 Now, if I make a copy--

87
00:04:03,780 --> 00:04:04,900
 not exactly a copy.

88
00:04:04,900 --> 00:04:08,900
 When I say y equals x, that makes a new y

89
00:04:08,900 --> 00:04:11,500
 that points at the same place.

90
00:04:11,500 --> 00:04:16,740
 And that's why, if we do an x.append world and print y,

91
00:04:16,740 --> 00:04:19,500
 we see hello world, even though we appended to x.

92
00:04:19,500 --> 00:04:25,500
 And that is because y and x are pointing to the same place.

93
00:04:25,500 --> 00:04:31,480
 So y equals x is not copying, as we might expect in the drawer

94
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:32,020
 analogy.

95
00:04:32,020 --> 00:04:33,300
 It's not copying it.

96
00:04:33,300 --> 00:04:35,340
 It's just adding a new pointer.

97
00:04:35,340 --> 00:04:40,020
 Now, sometimes you actually want to make

98
00:04:40,020 --> 00:04:41,300
 a full copy of something.

99
00:04:41,300 --> 00:04:43,380
 You got a list?

100
00:04:43,380 --> 00:04:45,340
 You want an independent list.

101
00:04:45,340 --> 00:04:48,780
 And so this is a pattern that we would call a copy constructor.

102
00:04:48,780 --> 00:04:50,780
 There's other ways to describe this.

103
00:04:50,780 --> 00:04:53,780
 We make a list, x equals list, print ID of x.

104
00:04:53,780 --> 00:04:54,940
 It's at a location.

105
00:04:54,940 --> 00:04:56,220
 We append hello to it.

106
00:04:56,220 --> 00:04:58,100
 x is in the same place.

107
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:03,020
 Now, instead of saying y equals x, we say y equals list parenx.

108
00:05:03,020 --> 00:05:05,860
 List is the constructor for lists.

109
00:05:05,860 --> 00:05:08,820
 And that says, read through the list x

110
00:05:08,820 --> 00:05:11,960
 and make full and independent copies of everything

111
00:05:11,960 --> 00:05:15,340
 in that list and make a new list and have y point to that.

112
00:05:15,340 --> 00:05:16,940
 That's what it's saying.

113
00:05:16,940 --> 00:05:19,940
 So if we say, where is y, print ID of y,

114
00:05:19,940 --> 00:05:22,820
 we see that the x is in one location

115
00:05:22,820 --> 00:05:25,940
 and the y is a list that's in another location.

116
00:05:25,940 --> 00:05:29,780
 And then if we add world to x and we print it,

117
00:05:29,780 --> 00:05:31,060
 we see hello world.

118
00:05:31,060 --> 00:05:33,840
 But y, because it's an independent copy stored

119
00:05:33,840 --> 00:05:38,340
 at a different location, print y just says hello.

120
00:05:38,340 --> 00:05:41,500
 So that is a copy constructor.

121
00:05:41,500 --> 00:05:46,060
 So if you ask ChatGPT, what's a Python variable?

122
00:05:46,060 --> 00:05:47,700
 ChatGPT is wrong.

123
00:05:47,700 --> 00:05:49,420
 It is bought into the simplification.

124
00:05:49,420 --> 00:05:51,220
 Now, if you dig in a little deeper,

125
00:05:51,220 --> 00:05:53,700
 you can say, are you sure it's not a location,

126
00:05:53,700 --> 00:05:56,060
 but it really a pointer to a location?

127
00:05:56,060 --> 00:05:58,060
 Blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

128
00:05:58,060 --> 00:06:01,840
 But perhaps it's because so many textbooks like mine

129
00:06:01,840 --> 00:06:05,340
 start in the beginning with that grand oversimplification.

130
00:06:05,340 --> 00:06:09,700
 Now, I'm very, very sorry to have misled you back

131
00:06:09,700 --> 00:06:11,500
 in Python for everybody.

132
00:06:11,500 --> 00:06:15,540
 But the notion of a variable being a drawer is not wrong.

133
00:06:15,540 --> 00:06:17,860
 It's just wrong in Python.

134
00:06:17,860 --> 00:06:21,920
 Things like languages like C or Fortran or COBOL,

135
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:24,000
 they tend to have this drawer model

136
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:26,260
 where the variable x is one drawer

137
00:06:26,260 --> 00:06:27,820
 and the variable y is another drawer

138
00:06:27,820 --> 00:06:29,420
 and they have independent things.

139
00:06:29,420 --> 00:06:32,720
 When you get around to it, when you learn C,

140
00:06:32,720 --> 00:06:35,780
 and I recommend my C programming for everybody course,

141
00:06:35,780 --> 00:06:40,700
 www.ccfree.com, in chapters five and six of that,

142
00:06:40,700 --> 00:06:43,740
 you learn about pointers and data.

143
00:06:43,740 --> 00:06:46,780
 And the difference, the key here is that Python

144
00:06:46,780 --> 00:06:48,180
 was written in C.

145
00:06:48,180 --> 00:06:52,860
 In the internal implementation of Python, it's C code.

146
00:06:52,860 --> 00:06:55,140
 And so the notion of a pointer and the data

147
00:06:55,140 --> 00:06:58,700
 that the pointer points to is completely natural in C.

148
00:06:58,700 --> 00:07:00,980
 It's just been sort of hidden for us.

149
00:07:00,980 --> 00:07:04,020
 We can take a look at it using the ID function

150
00:07:04,020 --> 00:07:06,060
 and get a sense of how variables

151
00:07:06,060 --> 00:07:08,500
 and assignment statements really work.

152
00:07:08,500 --> 00:07:11,480
 So again, sorry to have misled you.

153
00:07:11,480 --> 00:07:14,020
 I guess it's better late than never for me to talk to you

154
00:07:14,020 --> 00:07:17,380
 about the real way that assignment statements work

155
00:07:17,380 --> 00:07:18,340
 in Python.

156
00:07:18,340 --> 00:07:19,180
 Cheers.

157
00:07:19,180 --> 00:07:21,760
 (upbeat music)

